				\begin{document}$${TEE}(t)= \,	{{RMR}}_{{{Tb}}_{{ref}},{{BW}}_{{ref}}}{{{\rm{\cdot }}}}\cdot {Q}_{10}^{\left(\frac{{Tb}(t)-{{Tb}}_{{ref}}}{10}\right)}\cdot {\left(\frac{{BW}}{{{BW}}_{{ref}}}\right)}^{0.5}\\ 	 +{k}_{{PAEE}}\cdot {BW}\cdot {{PA}}_{\tau }(t)$$\end{document}TEE(t)=RMRTbref,BWref⋅⋅Q10Tb(t)−Tbref10⋅BWBWref0.5+kPAEE⋅BW⋅PAτ(t)Where TEE(t) and Tb(t) are the measured TEE and Tb in each time interval and PAτ(t) is the PA at each time interval smoothed using the time constant of the CLAMS system (5 min). BW is that measured for each mouse. The \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{{{\rm{RMR}}}}}_{{{{{\rm{Tb}}}}}_{{{{\rm{ref}}}}},{{{{\rm{BW}}}}}_{{{{\rm{ref}}}}}}$$\end{document}RMRTbref,BWref is the RMR of a mouse with Tb = Tbref and BW = BWref. Tbref was set to 37 °C and BWref was set to 28 g. Q10 is the van’t Hoff coefficient, set to 3.034 and kPAEE is the mass-specific energy cost of PA. The model was applied to a total of 396 h of data pooled from 23 mice, yielding kPAEE = 0.877 cal/1000 beam breaks/g BW and RMR37 °C,28g = 0.215 kcal/h. These kPAEE and RMR37 °C,28g values were used to calculate the contributions of Tb (Q10 effect) and PA (PAEE) to the TEE increase at Ta > 33 °C. The thermic effect of food was calculated as 11.8% of the metabolizable content of the caloric intake.
